author: @puidemare2337
text: I think the problem with this idea of being an "influencer" and "changing" society is a very dangerous one.  Suggesting that Jay become this kinda "guru" by virtue of stating his opinions is not healthy.  It encourages people to look outside for validation, rather, than within oneself.  It further fractures the family and tribal(community) unit.  I think this is the reason why we have so much dis-ease and discontentment within current society.  People are directionless, with no meaning in their life because they are so heavily influenced by celebrity/media ideologies.  I respect that Jay is apprehensive about telling people how to live.  We are all individuals with our own history and life experiences.  There is no blueprint on how to live.  What works for Jay may not work for someone else.  Our life experiences are for us to go through and hopefully learn and grow from.

LA realidad es que el hecho que √Ålex capitalice la conversaci√≥n, provoca que ellos pasen autom√°ticamente a un segundo plano de importancia, que entra en contradicci√≥n con su posici√≥n en la mesa (frente al espectador, y sin decir apenas nada hasta muy adelante). Mi SUGERENCIA (que se puede tirar ala papelera si n problemas, si no convence) ser√≠a montar el programa en peque√±os cap√≠tulos, como si de una comida se tratara, siguiendo el esquema de la comida en la que discurra.
